Client connection in dataplex
What does "Client connection" mean?
Instead of creating Data Scans manually from the GCP Console, you can control Dataplex using Python code.
The first step is to create a connection (client) to the Dataplex service.
Example:
from google.cloud import dataplex_v1

client = dataplex_v1.DataScanServiceClient()
Here:
•	google.cloud.dataplex_v1 → Dataplex Python SDK
•	DataScanServiceClient() → Creates a client that communicates with the Dataplex API.
Think of it like this:
Python Program
       │
       ▼
Dataplex Python Client
       │
       ▼
Dataplex API
       │
       ▼
Google Cloud Dataplex
The client acts as a bridge between your Python code and the Dataplex service.
________________________________________
What is "Run Scan"?
Once the client is connected, you can tell Dataplex to run a scan.
Example:
request = dataplex_v1.RunDataScanRequest(
    name=scan_name
)

client.run_data_scan(request=request)
This tells Dataplex:
"Run the Data Scan named sales-profile-scan."
Dataplex then starts scanning the registered BigQuery table or Cloud Storage asset.
________________________________________
What happens when the scan runs?
Suppose your BigQuery table is:
retail_demo.sales_clean
Dataplex scans the table.
For a Profile Scan, it collects information such as:
•	Number of rows
•	Number of columns
•	NULL values
•	Minimum value
•	Maximum value
•	Average
•	Duplicate count
•	Data distribution
For a Quality Scan, it checks your business rules, such as:
•	sale_id must be unique
•	customer_id must not be NULL
•	price must be greater than 0
Then Dataplex produces a report showing which rules passed or failed.
